<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1065,2026]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1065,1090]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body weakly stellate to pentagonal. Abactinal plates, flat, bare central surface, polygonal, no surficial granulation but with crystalline nodules/tubercles or radiating patterns present on subsurface. Marginal plates relatively few per interradius, with widely spaced coarse granules but otherwise smooth or bare. Actinal surface covered by granules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1065,2026]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1209,1234]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[347,472,1209,1234]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,472,1209,1234]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
along with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher 1906:" authorityYear="1056" box="[621,776,1210,1233]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroceramus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[621,776,1210,1233]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Astroceramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[841,961,1209,1234]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sibogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[841,961,1209,1234]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Sibogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are among several 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mah &amp; Foltz" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[1200,1356,1209,1234]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
which display crystalline nodules embedded in the abactinal plate surface and which also possess bald, smooth abactinal plates with few to no granules on the marginal surface. These differ from others, such as 
<emphasis box="[1189,1294,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Stellaster</emphasis>
and various members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Mah" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[333,456,1317,1342]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ferdininae">Ferdininae</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2017" box="[555,684,1317,1342]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Kanakaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[555,684,1317,1342]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Kanakaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which display crystalline nodules in conjunction with a granulated tegument covering the surface. Based on historical definitions from the literature (e.g 
<bibRefCitation author="Doderlein, L." box="[1228,1424,1353,1378]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="49 - 69" refId="ref69892" refString="Doderlein, L. (1924) Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. II. Pentagonasteridae. Siboga-Expedition, 46 (2), 49 - 69, pls. 14 - 19. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11319" type="journal article" year="1924">Doderlein, 1924</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[151,274,1389,1414]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,274,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher 1906:" authorityYear="1056" box="[301,456,1390,1413]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroceramus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[301,456,1390,1413]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Astroceramus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[535,655,1389,1414]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sibogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[535,655,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Sibogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have shown relatively distinct morphological boundaries, but examination of further diversity within each suggests overlap between them. Smaller sized (R=5.0) 
<taxonomicName box="[1270,1389,1425,1450]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sibogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1270,1389,1425,1450]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Sibogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for example superficially resemble very stellate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[688,812,1461,1486]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[688,812,1461,1486]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[e.g. “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macan" authorityYear="1938" box="[903,1191,1461,1486]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Eugoniaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[903,1191,1461,1486]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Eugoniaster ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” in 
<bibRefCitation author="Macan, T. T." box="[1254,1425,1462,1486]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="324 - 432" refId="ref71993" refString="Macan, T. T. (1938) Asteroidea. British Museum of Natural History, John Murray Expedition 1933 - 34, Scientific Reports, IV (9), 324 - 432." type="journal article" year="1938">Macan (1938)</bibRefCitation>
]. Similarly, pentagonal shaped or small-sized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher 1906:" authorityYear="1056" box="[647,803,1498,1522]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroceramus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="110" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Astroceramus</taxonomicName>
can also superficially resemble 
<emphasis box="[1162,1291,1497,1522]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[1162,1287,1497,1522]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Plinthaster</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1065,2026]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perrier" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[199,426,1533,1558]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="dentatus">
<emphasis box="[199,426,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster dentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs widely in the Atlantic and possibly in the south Pacific is morphologically varied leading to a wide synonymy. A comprehensive survey of Indo-Pacific 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[1009,1134,1569,1594]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1134,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has never been undertaken but it seems likely, based on unpublished observations, that there is considerable, if not greater variation among Pacific species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1065,2026]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,1245,1676,1702]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
What are 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[329,456,1676,1701]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[329,456,1676,1701]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(ex. 
<taxonomicName box="[524,690,1678,1701]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[524,690,1678,1701]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pentagonaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[713,829,1676,1701]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="doderleini">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[713,829,1676,1701]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">döderleini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alcock" authorityYear="1893" box="[849,1036,1676,1701]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatoris">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[849,1036,1676,1701]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. investigatoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koehler" authorityYear="1909" box="[1106,1224,1676,1701]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuenoti">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1106,1224,1676,1701]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. cuenoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
?.
</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[1259,1436,1677,1702]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref71539" refString="Koehler, R. (1910) An account of the shallow-water Asteroidea. Echinoderma of the Indian Museum, 6, 1 - 192. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11614" type="journal article" year="1910">Koehler (1910)</bibRefCitation>
described three Indian Ocean species of 
<emphasis box="[639,807,1714,1737]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName box="[639,802,1714,1737]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Pentagonaster</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which have found current assignment to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[1311,1436,1713,1738]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1311,1436,1713,1738]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macan" authorityYear="1938" box="[271,548,1749,1774]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[271,548,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[569,1137,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[569,863,1749,1774]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatoris">Plinthaster investigatoris</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[883,1137,1749,1774]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="doderleini">Plinthaster döderleini</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1207,1428,1749,1774]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuenoti">
<emphasis box="[1207,1428,1749,1774]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster cuenoti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macan" authorityYear="1938" box="[151,424,1785,1810]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ephemeralis">
<emphasis box="[151,424,1785,1810]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster ephemeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found to be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Doderlein 1924" authorityName="Doderlein" authorityYear="1924" box="[817,1239,1785,1810]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sibogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="digitatus">
<emphasis box="[817,1047,1785,1810]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Sibogaster digitatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Doderlein, L." box="[1059,1239,1785,1810]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="49 - 69" refId="ref69892" refString="Doderlein, L. (1924) Die Asteriden der Siboga-Expedition. II. Pentagonasteridae. Siboga-Expedition, 46 (2), 49 - 69, pls. 14 - 19. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11319" type="journal article" year="1924">Döderlein 1924</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L." box="[1291,1432,1785,1810]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="211 - 228" refId="ref72184" refString="Mah, C. L. (2015) New species, corallivory, in situ video observations and overview of the Goniasteridae (Valvatida, Asteroidea) in the Hawaiian Region. Zootaxa, 3926 (2), 211 - 228. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3926.2.3" type="journal article" year="2015">Mah (2015)</bibRefCitation>
. Evaluation of these other two species further suggests that assignment to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[1025,1150,1821,1846]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1025,1150,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unwarranted. In both species, the number of marginal plates (~25–34) per interradius is high and exceeds the number present in any of the known 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[275,399,1893,1918]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[275,399,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. The abactinal plate patterns and plate morphology, as described for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[1256,1436,1894,1917]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatoris">
<emphasis box="[1256,1436,1894,1917]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. investigatoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[201,381,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[201,346,1929,1954]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="doderleini">P. döderleini</taxonomicName>
as
</emphasis>
figured by Alcock (1893) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[744,919,1929,1954]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref71539" refString="Koehler, R. (1910) An account of the shallow-water Asteroidea. Echinoderma of the Indian Museum, 6, 1 - 192. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11614" type="journal article" year="1910">Koehler (1910)</bibRefCitation>
respectively, suggest that these species have been incorrectly assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[471,594,1965,1990]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[471,594,1965,1990]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Plinthaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1065,2026]" lastBlockId="72.[151,1437,151,861]" lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
The description of 
<taxonomicName box="[412,724,2002,2025]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatori">
<emphasis box="[412,724,2002,2025]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pentagonaster investigatori</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s Alcock indicates that the abactinal plates are tabulate, and are distinctly isolated from one another but with a fringe of squamous membrane clad granules flush with the general surface and with marginal plates bearing a small central, elevated patch of deciduous granules. A 
<typeStatus box="[1237,1285,189,213]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">type</typeStatus>
specimen for this species is unavailable and is most likely lost, but based on the description, this species seems best assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[151,303,260,285]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,303,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[508,662,260,285]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[508,662,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display the same general body shape, small, irregular abactinal plate pattern, raised granulated marginal patches and granules on the abactinal surface. The marginal plate number and furrow spine number are also more similar to other known 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[812,966,332,357]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[812,966,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Koehler" authorityYear="1909" box="[199,494,367,392]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="doderleini">
<emphasis box="[199,494,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pentagonaster döderleini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s description in 
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler, R." box="[710,892,367,392]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref71539" refString="Koehler, R. (1910) An account of the shallow-water Asteroidea. Echinoderma of the Indian Museum, 6, 1 - 192. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11614" type="journal article" year="1910">Koehler (1910)</bibRefCitation>
is also very compatible with placement in 
<emphasis box="[151,309,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[151,306,404,429]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Pillsburiaster</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Similarities are similar to those observed in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[815,995,405,428]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatoris">
<emphasis box="[815,995,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">P. investigatoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in terms of marginal plate number and irregular abactinal plate pattern. 
<taxonomicName authority="Koehler" authorityName="Koehler" authorityYear="1909" box="[530,886,439,464]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pentagonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="cuenoti">
<emphasis box="[530,786,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pentagonaster cuenoti</emphasis>
Koehler
</taxonomicName>
that 
<bibRefCitation author="Fisher, W. K." box="[949,1165,439,464]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="1 - 547" refId="ref70312" refString="Fisher, W. K. (1919) Starfishes of the Philippine seas and adjacent waters. Bulletin of the United States National Museum, 3 (100), 1 - 547, 156 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.1126 / science. 50.1293.348" type="book chapter" year="1919">Fisher (1919: 260)</bibRefCitation>
thought was similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[151,283,477,500]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,283,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Ceramaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also displays characters, such as the abactinal plate pattern and marginal plate morphology, granulated raised marginal patch and marginal plate number that are most compatible with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[1042,1195,511,536]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1042,1195,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Absence of granules on the surface of the abactinal plates can be attributed to abrasion during collection or possibly variation as has been observed in collections of the Atlantic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[644,957,583,608]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="geographicus">
<emphasis box="[644,957,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster geographicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Neither description of the above species mentions the presence of crystalline nodules in the abactinal plate surface which is a synapomorphy of 
<emphasis box="[565,694,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1899" box="[565,690,655,680]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Plinthaster</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Also noteworthy is the extreme occurrence depth of both species, with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Koehler" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[211,461,692,717]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="doderleini">
<emphasis box="[211,461,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Plinthaster döderleini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from 
<quantity box="[648,737,692,717]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.16" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="2160.0">2160 m</quantity>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[798,981,693,716]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Plinthaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="investigatoris">
<emphasis box="[798,981,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">P. investigatoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<quantity box="[1057,1145,692,716]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.38" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="1380.0">1380 m</quantity>
which is consistent with collection depths (
<quantity box="[366,546,728,752]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="1500.0" valueMax="2200.0" valueMin="800.0">800 to 2200 m</quantity>
) of accepted 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Halpern" authorityYear="1970" box="[710,864,727,752]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Pillsburiaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[710,864,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pillsburiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. These two species are also consistent with 
<taxonomicName box="[151,283,765,788]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,283,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Ceramaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[337,438,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Peltaster</emphasis>
but descriptions of abactinal and marginal plate morphology are not as identical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,151,861]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
A search for the 
<typeStatus box="[397,456,800,824]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">types</typeStatus>
of these species in the MNHN collections was unsuccessful and it is likely that this material is lost.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
